Achieving efficient nonenzymatic replication of RNA is an important step toward 
the synthesis of self-replicating protocells that may mimic early forms of life. 
Despite recent progress, the nonenzymatic copying of templates containing mixed 
sequences remains slow and inefficient. Here we demonstrate that activating 
nucleotides with 2-aminoimidazole results in superior reaction kinetics and 
improved yields of primer extension reaction products. This new leaving group 
significantly accelerates monomer addition as well as trimer-assisted RNA primer 
extension, allowing efficient copying of a variety of short RNA templates with 
mixed sequences.

